WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:12.760
The goal of data science is to turn data into value fast.

00:00:12.760 --> 00:00:18.000
But in traditional enterprise data science, we see a friction between the agility that

00:00:18.000 --> 00:00:25.000
the data scientists need and the complexity of the enterprise, which leads to a start,

00:00:25.000 --> 00:00:28.799
a stop, and a wait pattern, which kills momentum.

00:00:28.799 --> 00:00:34.599
This could be waiting for procurement, security reviews, or waiting for infrastructure, or

00:00:34.599 --> 00:00:42.320
waiting for deployment, and perhaps always being stuck on outdated tools.

00:00:42.320 --> 00:00:45.400
The Posit Team Native App is designed to solve this.

00:00:45.400 --> 00:00:51.799
Firstly, it provides instant setup, so you get running in minutes, not weeks.

00:00:51.799 --> 00:00:55.680
Second, it removes the ops headaches.

00:00:55.680 --> 00:01:00.119
It's a fully managed service, so data scientists get the latest and greatest features with

00:01:00.119 --> 00:01:05.720
automatic upgrades, and platform teams don't have to worry about managing complex infrastructure

00:01:05.720 --> 00:01:07.080
or software.

00:01:07.080 --> 00:01:12.800
It is secure by default by running inside the Snowflake security perimeter, and it inherits

00:01:12.800 --> 00:01:16.800
and extends Snowflake's data governance.

00:01:16.800 --> 00:01:25.199
Finally, it delivers improved productivity with AI tools and a seamless development-to-deployment

00:01:25.199 --> 00:01:26.199
workflow.

00:01:26.199 --> 00:01:30.839
So let's see Posit Team in action.

00:01:30.839 --> 00:01:38.360
We'll do a demo today, and our job to be done is to deliver an interactive LLM-powered dashboard

00:01:38.360 --> 00:01:39.879
for our business stakeholders.

00:01:39.959 --> 00:01:46.440
We'll follow five steps, accessing the platform and data, exploring the data, iterating on

00:01:46.440 --> 00:01:52.919
our data product, deploying the artifact, and interacting with it as a business user.

00:01:52.919 --> 00:01:53.919
Let's get started.

00:01:53.919 --> 00:01:56.919
The first step for me is to access the platform.

00:01:56.919 --> 00:02:01.919
Unfortunately, with the Posit Team Native App, my start is almost instant.

00:02:01.919 --> 00:02:07.440
I can install this application from the Snowflake marketplace, and once it's installed, I can

00:02:07.440 --> 00:02:11.720
activate Workbench, which is my development environment, and Connect, which is my deployment

00:02:11.720 --> 00:02:16.320
environment, all within the same Posit Team Native App.

00:02:16.320 --> 00:02:22.119
So let's start with the development side and log into Workbench.

00:02:22.119 --> 00:02:28.199
I'm going to start a new session, and I can choose any of these managed IDEs.

00:02:28.199 --> 00:02:33.240
For this demo, I'm going to use Positron, which is our next-gen polyglot IDE optimized

00:02:33.240 --> 00:02:34.240
for data science.

00:02:34.240 --> 00:02:37.800
This is where both Python and R are first-class citizens.

00:02:37.800 --> 00:02:41.320
One thing to note here is my session credential.

00:02:41.320 --> 00:02:46.399
These are all of the Snowflake roles which I have access to, and so here I'm logging

00:02:46.399 --> 00:03:00.639
with the role SolEng into my Positron IDE.

00:03:00.639 --> 00:03:07.839
One thing to note as this is coming up is that Workbench is automatically taking my

00:03:07.839 --> 00:03:13.399
credentials, my OAuth, and my role and securely inheriting it.

00:03:13.399 --> 00:03:17.839
We can see this if I just go into the terminal and look at my environment variables.

00:03:17.839 --> 00:03:20.919
You can see the SolEng role as well as the Snowflake home.

00:03:20.919 --> 00:03:23.119
This is where my OAuth token is stored.

00:03:23.119 --> 00:03:28.080
So what this means is that when I run a code such as this, in which I'm connecting to the

00:03:28.080 --> 00:03:31.520
Lending Club database, it should just work.

00:03:31.520 --> 00:03:36.919
I don't have to expose any of my credentials.

00:03:36.919 --> 00:03:42.119
We can see here the connection to Snowflake has been created, and the Lending Club database

00:03:42.119 --> 00:03:44.160
is the IBIS expression.

00:03:44.160 --> 00:03:46.479
So again, notice what I did not do here.

00:03:46.479 --> 00:03:51.600
I didn't write any boilerplate connection code, manage API keys, I didn't expose any

00:03:51.600 --> 00:03:57.919
of my secrets, Workbench managed all of that, and I was able to connect with just one line

00:03:57.919 --> 00:04:00.720
of code.

00:04:00.720 --> 00:04:07.559
So now as I'm connected to this data, I would love to understand this more.

00:04:07.559 --> 00:04:12.160
This is where data scientists spend the majority of their time.

00:04:12.160 --> 00:04:22.040
And to accelerate this exploratory data analysis, we have introduced DataBot.

00:04:22.040 --> 00:04:27.359
DataBot is our AI agent that's designed to accelerate exploratory data analysis.

00:04:27.799 --> 00:04:31.640
So if you give DataBot a high-level instruction, it will write and execute code, analyze the

00:04:31.640 --> 00:04:35.320
output, and suggest next steps, keeping you in the loop the entire time.

00:04:35.320 --> 00:04:43.480
So I'm going to start with asking it to explore the Lending Club database that we just connected

00:04:43.480 --> 00:04:44.480
to.

00:04:44.480 --> 00:04:54.880
Right at the bat, you can see that it understood that we are connected to Snowflake, and the

00:04:54.880 --> 00:04:58.559
Lending Club data is an IBIS expression.

00:04:58.559 --> 00:05:05.040
And the reason it's able to do this is because DataBot works on top of Positron, and so it

00:05:05.040 --> 00:05:11.920
has context of my session variables, the plots that I generate, the connections that I have,

00:05:11.920 --> 00:05:17.600
and essentially what that means is that the outcome that you have from DataBot is very

00:05:17.600 --> 00:05:22.559
contextually aware, and so the EDA workflow is tailored to your environment.

00:05:23.519 --> 00:05:28.880
Great, so DataBot did some initial analysis, it found there were about two and a quarter

00:05:28.880 --> 00:05:32.239
million loans that are in this database.

00:05:32.239 --> 00:05:34.839
It provided us some key characteristics.

00:05:34.839 --> 00:05:41.279
And after that, it gives us a few hypotheses which might be relevant for us to explore

00:05:41.279 --> 00:05:42.279
further.

00:05:42.279 --> 00:05:49.200
Now I can go ahead and choose any one of these, or I can choose something that I want to explore

00:05:49.200 --> 00:05:50.200
myself.

00:05:50.200 --> 00:05:54.239
And here I am interested in the relationship between employment length and loan default

00:05:54.239 --> 00:05:55.640
rates.

00:05:55.640 --> 00:06:00.880
So let's provide that query to DataBot, and it will be off to the races.

00:06:00.880 --> 00:06:22.679
So as DataBot is doing this analysis, let's jump into our Snowflake account, go into our

00:06:22.679 --> 00:06:25.320
query history, and see what's happening here.

00:06:25.720 --> 00:06:32.959
So you can see these are the queries that DataBot is generating on my behalf to understand

00:06:32.959 --> 00:06:34.399
the data.

00:06:34.399 --> 00:06:41.000
And you can see these are not simple select star from and downloading all of the data

00:06:41.000 --> 00:06:46.799
into your session memory, but they're involved SQL queries that it is running so that the

00:06:46.799 --> 00:06:54.160
computation can be pushed to the scalable Snowflake warehouses versus doing that within

00:06:54.160 --> 00:06:55.160
memory.

00:06:55.160 --> 00:06:58.519
And we should be able to see this here.

00:06:58.519 --> 00:07:05.839
So if you look at the data table here, you can see a total of about 50 to 60 rows that

00:07:05.839 --> 00:07:11.480
it has imported on a two and a half million database.

00:07:12.480 --> 00:07:19.399
So we see here that DataBot found some insights, found some missing employment data, and some

00:07:19.399 --> 00:07:21.399
interesting patterns.

00:07:21.399 --> 00:07:22.799
And this is interesting.

00:07:22.799 --> 00:07:30.000
It seems like there is a inverse U-shaped curve in terms of the relation between employment

00:07:30.000 --> 00:07:33.839
length and default rate, and it provides us some business implications there.

00:07:33.839 --> 00:07:39.399
And so we can go ahead and go dive deeper into any one of these.

00:07:39.399 --> 00:07:46.720
But another thing I could do here is say, hey, all right, I want to re-branch my analysis.

00:07:46.720 --> 00:07:51.799
This is a hypothesis that I'm not so interested in exploring further.

00:07:51.799 --> 00:07:57.559
So I just go back and ask it to, for instance, in this case, analyze geographical patterns

00:07:57.559 --> 00:08:02.040
in loan performance.

00:08:02.040 --> 00:08:06.720
And it starts doing this analysis as a different branch.

00:08:06.720 --> 00:08:14.440
And I can switch between different branches and go to one which is more relevant.

00:08:14.440 --> 00:08:19.359
So this is almost like a get branch for analysis, see which one's most promising and go for

00:08:19.359 --> 00:08:20.359
that one.

00:08:20.359 --> 00:08:22.279
So let's go back to the geographical pattern analysis that's happening.

00:08:36.719 --> 00:08:46.159
Perfect.

00:08:46.159 --> 00:08:51.000
So DataBot has gone and done some analysis around the regional patterns, found some economic

00:08:51.000 --> 00:08:57.479
correlations, and some key insights around clustering and so on.

00:08:57.479 --> 00:09:04.239
And this is, out of the two branches of analysis, I feel that the geographical pattern analysis

00:09:04.239 --> 00:09:06.719
is something which is more promising.

00:09:06.719 --> 00:09:12.000
And so at this stage, I'm like, OK, I want to make sure that this is reproducible.

00:09:12.000 --> 00:09:16.679
Maybe I share it with my peer or just share it with myself for posterity.

00:09:16.679 --> 00:09:24.000
So that's where I can use something like SlashReport, which is going to create a Quarter file which

00:09:24.000 --> 00:09:28.359
is reproducible where I have all of my code.

00:09:28.359 --> 00:09:32.320
And before it does that, it actually provides a report outline because this is the actual

00:09:32.320 --> 00:09:33.320
output.

00:09:33.400 --> 00:09:36.840
So I want to make sure that the plan is something which makes sense to me.

00:09:36.840 --> 00:09:40.119
And I'm going to just go ahead and say, yes, this outline looks fine.

00:09:40.119 --> 00:09:44.039
But you can definitely edit it if there are certain parts of the analysis that you wanted

00:09:44.039 --> 00:09:45.039
to highlight.

00:09:45.039 --> 00:09:50.799
And you see here, the Quarto document has started out.

00:09:50.799 --> 00:09:57.000
There is a call out that this has been created by AI, and there is a place for human review

00:09:57.000 --> 00:09:59.520
along with the name, the role, and so on.

00:09:59.520 --> 00:10:05.320
And this will now create a clean file which is fully reproducible.

00:10:05.320 --> 00:10:10.359
So once this is done, we will have this available in our Explorer.

00:10:10.359 --> 00:10:13.400
You can see the Learning Lab, Geographical Analysis, or QMD.

00:10:13.400 --> 00:10:20.359
And this is, again, what DataBot is focused on, making sure we accelerate the data scientist's

00:10:20.359 --> 00:10:27.440
productivity by having a code first ethos as well as ensuring that the data scientist

00:10:27.440 --> 00:10:31.559
always stays in the loop, has reproducible artifacts.

00:10:31.559 --> 00:10:37.280
And so we're really excited about this innovation.

00:10:37.280 --> 00:10:45.359
Now that my EDA process is complete, I can go to the next step.

00:10:45.359 --> 00:10:52.200
I've already used my insights to build this Shiny for Python app, which will query the

00:10:52.200 --> 00:10:54.479
Lending Club database.

